bug.short_desc: ant-contrib.jar left open after build file access, so cannot delete project contents.

long_desc.thetext:
That ant-contrib.jar is used by my build.xml file. It is kept open by at least one of the build.xml editor and the Ant view, even when I try to delete the entire Eclipse project containing both build.xml and ant-contrib.jar.
For the record: That ant-contrib.jar is accessed from the build file via the usual <taskdef><classpath> mechanism.
Unfortunately, I'm forced to work with an OS which has the design flaw (imho): "A file cannot be removed from a directory as long as some programm still has that file open."
Both bugs combine with this result: I cannot cleanly delete the project from the eclipse workspace, when using the option to also delete the project's contents from file space.
As I have little hope to get the OS design flaw fixed, I boldly ask you to please work around it.
Here are the details of what I actually do:
Check out that project into an eclipse workspace (that's already populated with some other projects).
Open the build.xml file with the (Ant) file editor. Maybe change a line or two, and save.
Open that same build.xml file with the Ant view (build runner). Use that to run a certain build.
Afterwards, I no longer need the build project. I choose "delete project" and use the option to also delete the entire thing from the workspace's file space.
That content-deletion fails, as eclipse still has ant-contrib.jar open.
Workaround: After the unsucessful delete, close eclipse. Ignore any messages about the non-existing .project file. Reopen eclipse. Again attempt the delete. This time, it comes through.
Suggested behaviour: When I delete a project, all editors and views that show files from that project should first close themselves automatically, before the deletion is attempted. At that same time, all OS file accesses to files in the project should terminate.
Regards, and thank you for providing fine software,
Andreas Krüger

bug.short_desc: FileServiceSubsystem doesnt forward exception info from Services

long_desc.thetext:
Various errors that occur on a file subsystem are not presented to the user - supposedly because SystemMessageException is caught away in most FileServiceSubsystem methods.
Example: mkdir notPermitted && chmod 0 notPermitted echo "test" > notPermitted.txt && chmod 0 notPermitted.txt
* dbl click notPermitted.txt -> empty file is shown in editor --> expect to see an excection that permission is denied * edit notPermitted.txt and save -> no error is shown --> this is critical because user-edited text may be lost! --> expect to see an exception that save permission is denied * delete notPermitted or notPermitted.txt * move a file into "notPermitted" directory --> an unsepecific error message is shown --> expect to see the original reason for the problem
This problem block bug 149181. It is critical because user-edited text can be lost.
Dave - I'd like to see this fixed for M4 since it will help us get more feedback on error reporting, and the possibility that user-edited content is lost is critical.

I've updated the dstore file service to use the new ISystemMessageProvider to get messages for the creation of SystemMessageExceptions. Those are thrown from that layer and now the FileServiceSubSystem catches them and displays the messages. The other services should be able to throw the exceptions now.
Fix verified in RC3 testing.

bug.short_desc: [hotbug] [j2ee] Bad import generated for package class from referenced generator model

long_desc.thetext:
We have models which depend on the j2ee models in WTP, so our genmodels reference the WTP j2ee.genmodel. The properties for the "Taglib" EMF package in the j2ee model specifies a package suffix for interfaces of "internal".
When we generate code for our models, the generated package classes for our models have generated import statements for "import org.eclipse.jst.j2ee.taglib.TaglibPackage" instead of "import org.eclipse.jst.j2ee.taglib.internal.TaglibPackage", resulting in compile errors.
After discussion with Ed Merks, the problem is actually in the j2ee.genmodel file, the package suffix for "Metadata" needs to be specified as "internal" for this to work.

bug.short_desc: .metadata and .log should not be hidden

long_desc.thetext:
The Mac does not use the convention of hiding files such as .metadata and /metadata/.log by prefixing them with a period. (Or at least it doesn;t treat these files the same as most other Unixes do.) You most especially should not do this with files you occasionally want the user to see. For example, when there's an error at startup Eclipse tells me to look in .metadata/.log. However this file is not accessible using the Funder, an editor, or any standard Mac tool. I can get to it by using the terminal, but I'm an old Unix geek. While I'd sort of expect most programmers to know how to do this:
A) It's still a pain in the posterior compared to using the Finder B) Many of my university students who use Eclipse do not know these sort of things
The Mac convention would probably put these files somewhere like ~/Library/Application Support; or, if they really do need to be in the same directory as the workspace, in a metadata directory that does not begin with a period.

------- Comment #4 From Robert Elliot 2006-08-17 11:59 [reply] -------
Yes. The M2Eclipse basically creates another classpath container (I think that's the term) containing all jars referenced in the POM and their dependencies (Maven2 does transitive dependencies). In physical terms these are located in your local Maven2 repository.
The J2EE publish correctly publishes the contents of the defined webapp folder and sticks the compiled classes into WEB-INF/classes, as you'd expect - but it doesn't know anything about this Maven2 classpath container so it ignores it. Instead as you know it deals with the modules defined in the .component file. You can of course add the same modules to the .component file or physically copy them into the WEB-INF/lib folder, but this is a chore, results in duplicate classpath entries and is generally a nasty workaround.
To do this properly you would need to do additional logic on the Maven2 classpath container; the Maven2 POM will define all jars needed in order to compile, including servlet.jar - it marks those that should not be included in the WEB-INF/lib folder as "compile" - and all of them are added to the Maven2 classpath container by the M2Eclipse plugin. So some work would be needed to work out which should be published by the J2EE plugin and which should not.
I see two possibilities:
1) Explicit support for Maven2 in WTP. This would mean that WTP was aware of POMs and calculated what to publish direct from the POM. It would mean duplicating a lot of the work done by the M2Eclipse team (unless the M2Eclipse plugin was incorporated into Eclipse like Ant? I believe the M2Eclipse team were interested in that at one point...). It would also mean that if you used the M2Eclipse plugin and WTP at the same time you would get duplicate classpath entries as they both processed the POM and added entries in different places.
2) WTP decoupled from Maven2 but able to be linked together by a 3rd party plugin like M2Eclipse via appropriate extension points. This is essentially what's going on with the JDT. This currently works pretty well, since you can set the webapp and src folders to match those in the POM - it only fails on the publishing of Maven2 defined dependencies.

I have been wondering if providing ClasspathContainer specific to the scope of dependencies would help in the integration and would be interested in any feedback.
Currently there is only one classpath container for all dependencies - I have been wondering whether adding one for runtime, one for test, one for provided etc. In this sense it would be easier to exclude test libs from a run etc and also I'm wondering whether we could implement an interface on the container for WTP so that provided/test could be excluded at the container level?

So I guess that it's a bit of the work that can be done now on the M2Eclipse plugin without any decision needing to be made about WTP, and will speed things up if the WTP decision is to offer some means to allow plugins to over-ride the way it calculates project modules.

All classpath container entries allow to have unlimited number of attributes (including custom stuff), that is how javadoc attachment is implemented and m2 plugin already fill in some of those attributes from the pom. This is dangerous because now you are running a much higher risk of having duplicate classpath entries which will cause the project to fail to compile. This can be overcome by trimming the calculated entries from the container but which container wins? This also means that containers would have to be aware of each other.
It sounds like what you want is a way to add a "container" like element to the module definition of an EAR project or a Web project (in the case of Web libs). This container would dynamically calculate the contents that should be packaged with the parent and would be added to the classpath. This is easier done for Web libs than EARs. Within the EAR project and the other module projects there already exists the Module classpath container that calculates the module dependenies based on the Manifest and the .component files. I would break this support into two categories.
1) The ability to add a dynamic container to an EAR or Web project to calculate additional utility JARs to be included in the packaging (and on the classpath). 2) The ability to add a dynamic container to an EAR to calculate additional modules to be included in the EAR.
The first category would be easier than the second. The problem with the second is that it overlaps with the current mechanism so much.
As a final note. I would rather see the Maven support added as an extension to the current WTP functionality. Which means we explore what, if anything, would need to be changed in WTP to enable this functionality.

bug.short_desc: Around advice weaving generates repeated methods

long_desc.thetext:
Shadow extraction and advice inlining in around advice weaver generate repeated methods for occurrences of an identical shadow on a same class. This is an example:
public class BugExample { public static void main(String[] args) { new BugExample().run(); } private void run() { int x = foo(-5); int y = foo(1); int z = foo(2); int w = foo(0); System.out.println("x=" + x + " y=" + y + " z=" + z + " w=" + w); } private int foo(int v) { return v; } public static aspect BugAspect { pointcut fooCalls(int v): call(* BugExample.foo(int)) && args(v); int around(int v): fooCalls(v) { if (v > 0) return proceed(v); else return 0; } } }
The result of "javap -c -private BugExample" is at the end of this report (it's rather big). In it you may realize that there is no difference between the several proceed methods, and the only difference between the several advice inline methods is which proceed method invoked (and since those are equivalent, there is no semantic difference between the advice methods either).
I have fixed this problem by applying an aspect to the AspectJ weaver, which caches shadow and advice methods and reuses them as possible. This is done by capturing calls to BcelShadow.extractShadow and avoiding such calls if a method with the same signature has already been created. The same is done for the creation of local advice methods. Of course, this only indicates a path to a (pure Java) final solution.

long_desc.thetext:
When I open a page in the welcome and tab through the section links in the top banner, JAWS7 does not announce the name of each link. Instead, it reads "icon slash blank link graphic".
1. Open the welcome. 2. Click on one of the section links; for example "Overview". 3. Tab to the Overview link in the banner nav. JAWS7 says "icon slash blank link graphic." I expected it to also say "Overview." 4. Tab to the Tutorials link. JAWS7 says "icon slash blank link graphic", not "Tutorials." The same applies for each of the section links.
This is a real problem if you can't see which link is in focus - you have no idea where you are in the banner nav.
(FYI - the names of the section links on the root/front page of the welcome do get announced by JAWS7 when I tab through each of them...)
Created an attachment (id=48108) Screen capture of the welcome banner nav items
*** Bug 154252 has been marked as a duplicate of this bug. ***
Dejan, can I fix this for 3.2.1? I will see if there is a straightforward fix and let you know the risk.

Here's the deal. JAWS appears to have a deficiency when it comes to reading formatted text links. The text of the link is wrapped in a span element in order to give it a class.
Overview I would consider this a bug in JAWS. There is certainly enough information here to formulate a text description. The obvious workaround is to add alt-text to the IMG. However this has a rather ugly side effect - IE mistakenly treates alt-text as tooltips. Normally this is fine but in this case we already have hover-over text so what happens is you see the welcome hover text, and then a second later the IE tooltip on top of it. It becomes difficult to read and annoying. I could not find any other recommendations or ways to work around this particular problem without adding some risk. So it seems we have to decide whether we want a subset of our users to suffer (those who rely on accessibility) and have to return back to the home page when they want to switch page, or annoy the rest of our users with an unnecessary tooltip. Any thoughts?
I am against using alt-text here.

In that case I think we need to back out for 3.2.1 on this one, if there are no objections. So users who rely on screenreaders will hear some garbage for the page navigation at the top, but they will still be able to access those pages by using the view toolbar buttons (back/next/home) to get back to the home page and select a link from there. Or they can just close and reopen welcome.
Either way they won't be stuck; they just won't be able to use this convenience shortcut.

Discussed this issue with the my accessibility contacts on the Constellation/ADC project mgmt team. They agree that "while this problem surely does generate a very poor user experience, due to the existing circumvention it does not break accessibility compliance." I can report compliance on this one for now, but request that it be fixed in Eclipse for the next release.
Alternative workarounds to be explored in 3.3.

bug.short_desc: Make synchronization of tasklist items use a single job or single progress indication

long_desc.thetext:
Currently we have multiple jobs appearing in the progress monitor. When synchronizing multiple queries or tasks, connector.synchronize(...) runs as a single job but this is called per connector which results in many jobs. Adding to this are the tasks sync jobs which may result from syncronization of queries. This can add up to a number of jobs being displayed in the progress monitor as Eugene has observed:
"I would definetely prefer single sync job. I usually have Progress view shown and those multiple and jumpy Mylar's jobs are quite annoying..."
Note that this will mean that a slow repository could hold up a fast one when synching.

For background synchronization all repositories are synchronized sequentially but in separate jobs. I would like to change that to either parallelize synchronization or use a single job. What is the preference here?
I am leaning towards a single job which makes it easy to cancel synchronization by clicking once and we need to make sure that manual synchronization is always prioritized so user interactions are not delayed up by the background synchronization job.

One of the advantages of multiple jobs is that you can actually skip/kill troublesome repository and it is unclear how that case can be supported with single job. Also need to make sure that if sync fail for one of the repositories, that job would continue to next repository.
So, it seem like parallel sync is more attractive, but it may open up some concurrent bugs, deadlocks or simply slow down environment (some of the parsing/decoding could eat cpu).

bug.short_desc: Abstract graph model nodes and connections into interfaces

long_desc.thetext: It would be nice if GraphModelNode and GraphModelConnection were abstracted into interfaces rather than necessarily being concrete classes. This would help make the implementation of the proxy nodes and connections be cleaner. Currently, there is a lot of unused data in the proxy nodes and connections because everything is delegated to the proxy. It is also hard to keep track of what should/should not be delegated right now.
Any discussion?

This makes sense.
These should not be subclassed outside of Zest, but when we first made this we didn't have the proxy nodes. I think ths is a good idea.
Do you think that the nested nodes should still extend graph node?

Created an attachment (id=48890) Patch
New interfaces: IGraphItem, IGraphModelNode, and IGraphModelConnection have been created to address this issue.
References to the concrete GraphModelNode and GraphModelConnection, and GraphItem have been removed where possible, and and replaced with the generic interfaces.
Proxy nodes and proxy connections have been updated to use the new interfaces. They do not extend the concrete GraphModelNode or GraphModelConnection.
NonNestedProxyNode now has the following behaviour:
All requests for basic visual information/changes are forwarded to the concrete node that it references. This information includes things like colour, text, font, etc. Information about layout, size, and selection are *not* forwarded t the concrete node, as this information is specific to the proxy itself.
ProxyConnections do *not* forward any method calls to the concrete connection that it references. ProxyConnections simply initialize their visual information from the referenced connection. This is because ProxyConnections are, themselves, new connections between new nodes. Discussion: should anything be excepted from this rule? For example, should labels/wieghts get updated with the referenced connection? How about colour?
This patch also addresses bug #154595: endpoint decorations on the connections are now sized according to the line width.
There are also some visual/performance enhancements for the PolylineArcConnection.

bug.short_desc: [Trim] [Commands] [GlobalActions] Trim contributions need a way to hook handlers

long_desc.thetext:
3.2
We have a trim contribution that contains a text field, and another that sometimes contains a text field, e.g. during a rename. It would be nice to support cut/copy/paste/delete/select all for these. This can probably be handled now by registering a handler with the window-level command service, but it would be better if localized service interfaces could be provided to trim contributions, as they are for workbench parts.
Likewise for other services (e.g. part service, selection service).
Nick, does it make sense to integrate the trim by making it a full-fledged WorkbenchPart? If you have time we should go over what you're looking for...

Discussed this with Eric. The main issue is that handlers for Cut/Copy/Paste etc. can't be registered for the trim item itself. Depending on whether the active part has handlers for these, Ctrl+V may work in the trim item, or it may get targeted to the active part. Either way, Edit>Paste doesn't work as expected.
While handlers can be registered on the window's handler service, this requires more code in the trim widget to manage its lifecycle, since the service isn't localized.
If coming up with a common view-like interface simplifies things, I'm all for it.

Another possiblity that comes to mind is to provide another Source with priority 1 << 28 that can track focusIn and focusOut for specified controls.
Then you would be able to provide handlers for that "level" and the framework would automatically activate/deactivate them.
PW

Paul, you'll have to drop by to explain the last comment..;-).
How do we detect part (view) activations? They must somehow be tracking when the part's interior structure gets 'selected' (focus?) without the actual part implementation being affected (i.e. -it- doesn't need special code to handle this...).

The active handler is determined by expression priority. The case we have here is that there's a default handler (WidgetMethodHandler) and a view part handler (whatever).
part priority > default priority, so the part handler always wins. There's a source for part information, but nothing in the framework currently that applies to controls.
So one possible solution would be to provide a source for controls ... I'd go with registered controls. If a registered control gets focus, handlers for the control would win out over handlers for the part. Thus WidgetMethodHandler could win while focus is in your trim text widget.
Later, PW

I think the issue here is they are using the EclipseStarter from the outside "container" of WAS which is Eclipse 3.1. This is because the WebApp classloader is using parent first so it finds the class from the "outer" Equinox framework. In order to launch multiple instances of Equinox in the same VM the Equinox framework must be loaded with separate classloaders for each instance. In this case it looks like you are using the EclipseStarter class which started WAS to attempt to launch another instance of Equinox but it has already launched Equinox once so it fails the second time you try to launch Equinox.
The servlet bridge in the server-side work sets up a classloader for the framework that does not delegate to the parent for the framework classes. This allows it to use a completely separate instance of the EclipseStarter class than the one from WAS to launch another instance of Equinox from the application.

Tom's on the mark here --
I think there are three areas that need to be addressed:
1) As mentioned, you need to use a child-first classloader to avoid accidentally loading the Eclipse 3.1 framework classes.
2) The System properties used to configure Eclipse 3.1 will conflict with your newly launched Equinox instance. Your instance should use "osgi.framework.useSystemProperties = false" and then directly set properties using "setInitialProperties" in EclipseStarter. In some cases you might have to null out existing properties that are inherited from WS 6.1.
3) osgi.parentClassLoader=fwk "might" still cause problems. We're better off to use "boot" or "ext" here and selectively expose those parts of the webapp needed.
-- The org.eclipse.equinox.servletbridge project in the main Eclipse depot has a FrameworkLauncher that comes very close to meeting your needs. Hi Susan,
> Excuse my naivete here, but I have some questions (embedded in your comments > below), about your suggestions Simon. -- no problem.
> > 1) As mentioned, you need to use a child-first classloader to avoid > > accidentally loading the Eclipse 3.1 framework classes. > Can this be set during the deployment of the BIRT web viewer application in > WAS? I know the WAS deployment console allows for this, but I was not sure if > this needed to be set somewhere else. WAS provides the ability to set child-first for the webapp class loader however in this case we're creating a URLClassloader to load resources from the jars in WEB-INF/platform/plugins. In other words we still are required to manually create a child-first classloader as WAS is unaware of the class loaders created inside the webapp.
> I noticed in the org.eclipse.birt.core.framework.osgi.OSGILauncher class in the > 2.2M2 version of BIRT the osgi.framework.useSystemProperties has been set to > false, and the setInitialProperties method of EclipseStarter is being used. > Do you know which properties need to be 'nulled out' from WAS 6.1? That's great. Off the top of my head the most important properties to either null out or set are: osgi.bundles (null) osgi.bundles.defaultStartLevel (null) osgi.parentClassloader osgi.contextClassLoaderParent osgi.framework osgi.instance.area osgi.configuration.area osgi.install.area
There might be others in the context of running BIRT however these are the ones I'd most worry about.
> It appears that osgi.parentClassLoader is still set to "fwk". When you say it > would be better off to use "boot" or "ext", is this true when using any app > server to deploy the BIRT vieweer app that might include the osgi framework > (ones other than WAS)? > If so, could you comment on why, and could a BIRT committer also comment on why > it is currently set to "fwk"? First, this is not just a WAS thing (although the associated problems are particularly bad there). The problem with setting parentClassLoader to "fwk" is that your OSGi instance is no longer isolated. The child-first classloader will apply to resources in org.eclipse.osgi however for all other resources the webapp classloader will be visible to every bundle. Some of the problems associated with this are version mismatches on package imports and unexpected results when working with singletons. On WAS you'll definitely have problems as for example the resources you think are loading from your org.eclipse.equinox.common in WEB-INF/platform/plugins are actually coming from the App Server.
The best way I've found in terms of integrating with OSGi is to use either "boot" or "ext" and then selectively expose resources from the webapp using framework extension bundles. In this way your resources from the webapp will participate properly in the bundle resolution process -- a good thing.
> Also, I concur with Jeff, it would be extremely helpful if the code is not > changed to allow this to at least have a wiki entry, or something that folks > can change to allow for deployment in environments that launch the osgi > framework. Yep. I agree and this is on the TODO list.

Thanks Simon. I appreciate the explanation and will watch this bug for more info.
Regards,
Susan

bug.short_desc: Need to create an annotation to help identify methods that must be called on dispatch thread.

long_desc.thetext:
The rules dictating which methods must be called on dispatch thread are very important in implementations using DSF. But it can be difficult from an API user's point of view to identify which methods require to be called on dispatch thread, and which methods are thread-safe.
I propose adding an annotation: DsfExecutorThreadAccessOnly (I'm open to suggestions for a better name), which will clearly idenify methods that must be called on the dispatch thread. We can then go through all existing DSF interfaces and add the annotation.
Still the annotation is only a documentation tool in this case, and assertions should still be used in methods that require dispatch thread access to catch bugs.

The annotation could be used to instrument the code to turn the annotations into exceptions (e.g. using AspectJ). If all objects are represented by interfaces, the framework could decorate the objects with a dynamic proxy that throws the exceptions.
But maybe, just doing the assert in the methods itself (like SWT) is the best way.

That's an interesting (about using AspectJ). Most of the methods are not thread-safe, so requiring an assert in every one of then seems wrong to me on principal.
In either case, I propose the following three annotations:
AccessInDsfExecutorThread("getSession().getExecutor().getExecutorThread()"); ThreadSafe Immutable (implies ThreadSafe)
Between these, any class and method in DSF services should have one of the annotations. Maybe to avoid typing, the AccessInDsfExecutorThread could be applied on the service interface itself and be "inherited" by all methods as a default.
The argument to AccessInDsfExecutorThread would tell the user (and any generic code) how to obtain the executor thread. Again this could be somewhat verbose though, and I don't know how an automatic tool could read it easily.

bug.short_desc: Improve performance of load...

long_desc.thetext:
XSDConcreteComponentImpl.getXSDContainer is much faster if eContainer instead of eContainer() is used. EnumerationFacetImpl.isConstraintSatisfied is much faster if an iterator is not used. XSDNamedComponentImpl.findInSortedList is much faster if there is a HashMap for the name lookup, because collated string comparison is grossly slow. XSDIdentityConstraintImpl needs to adopt into the schema before adding to the sorted list to that the namespace will be set properly. XSDSimpleTypeDefinitionImpl spends a lot of time on casting when processing facets and that would be much faster if the underlying typed array can be accessed. Also it should be possible to assess something to create a value without validating that value since the validation result is often ignored and is expensive to compute.
These changes result in improved load time of 200-400%.

bug.short_desc: Project-specific Java compliance should update build.properties

long_desc.thetext:
When I edit project-specific preferences in the JDT GUI, and change the compiler compliance settings to 1.4-with-assert, I'd expect the build.properties file to be updated automatically (javacSource, javacTarget properties).
This is necessary in order to support headless builds e.g. for creating an update site. If the build.properties file is not updated automatically, it's just too easy to break the headless build with something that seems to work fine in the UI build.
See also bug 148260

Modifying files (eg. build.properties) behind the user's back is not a good idea. Some users may want it, others would most certainly not.
The way to approach this is to flag the build.properties with a warning (along with a quickfix) if there is a mismatch between the project settings and the build.properties.
Good point, I agree.

(In reply to comment #1) > Modifying files (eg. build.properties) behind the user's back is not a good > idea. Some users may want it, others would most certainly not.
Can you give an example of when a user would want headless build to act differently than the PDE build? I cannot think of one.
> The way to approach this is to flag the build.properties with a warning (along > with a quickfix) if there is a mismatch between the project settings and the > build.properties.
Would this warning be issued by PDE Build? If so, the text of the warning should include a list of the build.properties that are out of sync. I do not think a simple "build.properties is out of sync" is sufficient.

FYI, perhaps the most important use-case for this is setting project level java compliance settings to "J2SE 1.4 with assert".
This requires setting Java compliance to source=1.4, target=1.4 in the project properties, and javacSource=1.4 javacTarget=1.4 in the build.properties file.
If this is not done, and user has java code with asserts, a UI action like creating an update site or exporting as deployable plug-in will issue errors that the user certainly can't understand.

I agree with martin that this is a problem. I also agree with Wassim that things should not happen behind the users back. And I do not want to see project settings automatically changing anything.
Fundamentally the issue is that the manifest's "Execution Environments" setting is specifying compilation settings. That is just wrong. Execution implies runtime. Its misleading. If there is to be a compliation setting in the manifest, it needs to include a checkbox for code compliance just like the project settings. Then eclipse can throw a warning when they do not match. Heck, eclipse can throw a warning now since the tricky issue is Sun making 1.4 compliance actually very 1.3ish. So Eclipse can see that project setting is allowing assert, but J2SE-1.4 environment setting does not.
Anyway, I still think the issue is "Execution environment." What is that used for anyway? Is it only a compilation setting, or does eclipse check this before it loads a plugin?
